Draft character-arc metadata: how each entity below CHANGES across the story.
The prose writer (a later stage) reads this per passage as "who this entity is
right now, and where they are heading" — it is what lets a scene foreground ONE
aspect of an entity instead of restating every known fact. It is never shown
to the player.

An arc is what makes an entity part of the story instead of scenery: a
character without an arc is an extra, a location a backdrop, an object a
mcguffin, a faction a link. Any of them can be given an arc. What an arc means
varies by kind: a character TRANSFORMS, a location's ATMOSPHERE shifts, an
object's SIGNIFICANCE grows or curdles, a faction's RELATIONSHIP to the
protagonist moves.

