For each entity worth arcing, propose {"entity": id, "begins": ..., "pivots":
[{"beat": id, "becomes": ...}, ...], "ends": [{"path": id, "state": ...}, ...]}:
- begins: who/what they are when the story opens — the ASPECT in play, one line.
- pivots: 1-4 turns, each anchored to the beat that turns it, in story order.
  From that beat on, the entity reads as "becomes". Anchor a pivot to the beat
  where the change HAPPENS, not where it is first useful.
- ends: for each explored path whose choice lands this entity somewhere
  different, where it lands. Omit paths that don't touch the entity.
- Arc every entity listed above whose state moves across the story. Leaving
  an entity unarced DECLARES it scenery — an extra, a backdrop, a mcguffin, a
  link. That is a legitimate call, but make it deliberately; arc at least one.
Every begins/becomes/state is a NOTE in plain declarative present tense — an
aspect and its direction ("grief held at arm's length", "the ledger becomes
evidence"), never prose, never imagery to reuse.
